% this file tests LaTeX annotations
This brings us to two new formulae. Define $f : \mathbb{N} \times \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{Z}$ by $f\left(a, b\right) = c$, where $c = a - b$. Define $g : \mathbb{N} \times \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{Z}$ by $g\left(a, b\right) = d$, where $d = a + b$. With these, we can define:
\refstepcounter{nbmAlgorithmCounter}
\label{my_algorithm_name}
{
\par
\centering
\fbox{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\dimexpr\linewidth-2\fboxsep-2\fboxrule}
\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Algorithm \thenbmAlgorithmCounter: My Algorithm Name}
\\
{\small This text provides a description of the algorithm}\vspace{0.5em}
\hrule
\vspace{-\abovedisplayskip}
\begin{flalign*}
&\text{Define}~h : \mathbb{N} \times \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{Q}~\text{by}&\\
&h\left(a, b\right) = \frac{e}{6}&\\
&\text{where}~e = abs\left(f\left(a, b\right) \cdot g\left(a, b\right)\right).&
\end{flalign*}
\end{minipage}%
}
\vspace{0.5em}
\par
}

To give some example values: 
$f\left(1, 2\right) = -1$, $g\left(1, 2\right) = 3$ and $h\left(1, 2\right) = \frac{1}{2}$.    % here we use evaluation fragments, which will be replaced by the evaluated results of the given expressions

Now, we can finally use Algorithm~\ref{my_algorithm_name} to...

...
Define $i : \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}$ by\\
$i\left(x\right) = id\left(x\right).$\refstepcounter{nbmProcedureCounter}
\label{doubling}
{
\par
\centering
\fbox{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\dimexpr\linewidth-2\fboxsep-2\fboxrule}
\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Procedure \thenbmProcedureCounter}
\vspace{0.5em}
\hrule
\vspace{-\abovedisplayskip}
\begin{flalign*}
&\text{Define}~k : \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}~\text{by}&\\
&k\left(x\right) = -2 \cdot neg\left(y\right)&\\
&\text{where}~y = i\left(x\right).&
\end{flalign*}
\end{minipage}%
}
\vspace{0.5em}
\par
}\refstepcounter{nbmAlgorithmCounter}

{
\par
\centering
\fbox{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\dimexpr\linewidth-2\fboxsep-2\fboxrule}
\vspace{0.5em}
\textbf{Algorithm \thenbmAlgorithmCounter: Another Great Algorithm}
\vspace{0.5em}
\hrule
\vspace{-\abovedisplayskip}
\begin{flalign*}
&\text{Define}~l : \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}~\text{by}&\\
&l\left(x\right) = x^{2}.&
\end{flalign*}
\end{minipage}%
}
\vspace{0.5em}
\par
}

Now, using Produce~\ref{doubling} together with this new algorithm, we can evaluate:
$l\left(k\left(-3\right)\right) = 36$